1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:15,000
I should have brought some water, I didn't think, but anyway.

3
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:18,000
Yeah, okay, no problem.

4
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:20,000
That is not really right.

5
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:24,000
Today is Wednesday, September 14, 2011.

6
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:30,000
This is Joe Mosnier of the Southern Oral History Program, University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

7
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:36,000
I'm with the videographer John Bishop on the campus of the University of Florida in Gainesville, Florida.

8
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:49,000
To do an interview for the Civil Rights History Project, which is a joint undertaking of the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

9
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:58,000
We're delighted to have the chance to sit down with Dr. Gwendolyn Zoharah Simmons to talk about a portion.

10
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:08,000
And I have to say probably just a portion because you have done so much work, but a portion of the work you've done in the struggle over the years and will be focusing mostly on the 1960s.

11
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:13,000
Thank you for welcoming us to Gainesville and campus and it's nice to be with you.

12
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:14,000
Thank you.

13
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:29,000
Let me start with, having you talk just a little bit about some of the first impressions that you took of the folks in the Atlanta SNCC when you began to turn your attention that way as a young college student.

14
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:42,000
Well, as I reflect back on going to the SNCC, as I recall, it was very chaotic.

15
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:47,000
It was a beehive of activity.

16
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:52,000
It certainly was not what I expected.

17
00:01:52,000 --> 00:02:06,000
It was often very untidy and phones ringing, people running around, lots of excitement.

18
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:18,000
And a couple of people, of course, James Forman or James Forman, being at the center of a lot of it.

19
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:35,000
Ruby Doris Smith Robinson, also a very important fixture there, with lots of other people, Black, White and Asian, which was a big surprise for me to meet two people who would become

20
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:41,000
lifelong colleagues as it turns out, who were Japanese Americans.

21
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:49,000
And so that was quite the first time I think I'd ever met a Japanese person.

22
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:54,000
So the place was jumping, as they say.

23
00:02:54,000 --> 00:02:57,000
You wouldn't have met Ella Baker, of course.

24
00:02:57,000 --> 00:03:26,000
She did not have an office in that office, but Miss Baker, I would see at our gatherings and our meetings, of course, when she, as long as I was a student going there, sort of hit and run, given that I was breaking one of Spelman College's prohibition on student political activity by even being at that location.

25
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:31,000
I had a lot of time on the sign-out sheets saying where I was going.

26
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:51,000
But of course, over the years, I had the great privilege of seeing Miss Baker at work, as she, in a very gentle and unobtrusive way and her knowledge.

27
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:55,000
And I was literally only if we ask.

28
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:59,000
But yes, she had a profound impact on me.

29
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:06,000
Yeah, and I'm sure, as we extend our conversation today, gender will be a question that emerges again and again.

30
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:17,000
I know that it's important to start even at the beginning with the acknowledgement of that being Miss Baker as a example of,

31
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:22,000
sort of, for example, raising so many questions that would think of them.

32
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:44,000
I'm interested to have you reflect a little bit about, and you have in some of your writings, obviously, about the tension, that that very basic tension between the pressures of family and in relative terms in this context, the conservative college campus and its administration, the pull you felt towards deeper involvement in a more direct way.

33
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:57,000
There was a terrible tension in my life, because I had been told by my folks not to get involved in no uncertain terms.

34
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:11,000
And as the first person in my family to graduate from high school, to go off to college on a full scholarship, I was, you know, very aware of how tenuous things were.

35
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:16,000
And then Spellman was adamant that we were not to get involved.

36
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:26,000
And in fact, had told us in freshman orientation that if they found out we were involved, we could lose our scholarships and be sent home.

37
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:37,000
So this was a terrible thing hanging over my head to know that if I got in trouble with the school, my parents were not going to back me up.

38
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:51,000
And yet the pull, as it began to, you know, really grip me, I literally cried on a number of occasions about this.

39
00:05:51,000 --> 00:06:12,000
And of course having Staughton Lynd, Dr. Staughton Lynd as a very important person in my early life there at Spellman, learning about the long struggle that black people had been engaged in since we were brought here.

40
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:17,000
And learning about it in a way that I never had learned of it.

41
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:31,000
And then to some extent, Howard Zinn, who was there on the campus and a radical force, and then Vincent Harding and his wife Vincent Harding,

42
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:43,000
who I met at the Mennonite House where I'd go for dinner on Sundays and to engage in the discussions that went on there.

43
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:50,000
They were pulling me toward the engagement and the SNCC folk who were my own age.

44
00:06:50,000 --> 00:07:02,000
Many of them, people who had already left school to work full time, they made it very clear what they thought about us who were still trying not to get involved.

45
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:13,000
And so there was a pull I was at sometimes felt as if I were being pulled a sunder.

46
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:32,000
And you've written about episodes, I'm remembering the rain shower, the sudden thunder shower outside the Memphis office buildings when you were downtown looking for a first job to find some additional funds for heading to college.

47
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:45,000
And just the more encompassing realities of Jim Crow, obviously, I know that those things obviously would have propelled anyone towards many people towards an engagement with the movement.

48
00:07:45,000 --> 00:08:01,000
But were there specific aspects of the personalities, the individuals you encountered in that group of core of SNCC folks, whose personal characteristics matter to great deal in the pull you felt towards the group?

49
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:10,000
Well, you know, it's interesting. I mean, I always saw James Forman as sort of my mentor, my early mentor.

50
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:16,000
And even though he was not a college-aged person, I was very impressed with him.

51
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:24,000
But Ruby D'Aris Robinson, you know, because she had dropped out of Spellman to work full time.

52
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:38,000
And so she was someone I could relate to, but it also frightened me to think, oh my God, I might do what she has done, drop out, and I know what my folks are going to say and do.

53
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:50,000
And, you know, the SNCC feel staff from Mississippi when they would come in. There were women in that group.

54
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:56,000
And these people were so brave, it seemed to me. I was very impressed with them.

55
00:08:56,000 --> 00:09:09,000
So I think the SNCC folk who really moved me the most were both Jim and Ruby D'Aris.

56
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:18,000
And then I got to know and really be friendly with John Lewis also. He had dropped out of school too.

57
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:25,000
And then the Nashville staff, you know, those people, they just blew me away, you know.

58
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:36,000
They're bravery, the stories of them being jailed and beaten. So I was scared to death too. But the fact that that had not turned them around.

59
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:44,000
And when they said it was time to change this, you know, it really struck home with me.

60
00:09:44,000 --> 00:09:54,000
Did you meet folks who had done the Albany work and were doing the Albany work at Charles Sherrod and Chuck McDew?

61
00:09:54,000 --> 00:10:04,000
I certainly did meet them later, particularly in my second year when I became a member of the coordinating committee, you know.

62
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:13,000
But there were so many people, you know, and for some reason that Mississippi staff, I mean I think we all,

63
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:22,000
sort of held them up as the heroes, you know. And so they were the ones that impressed me.

64
00:10:22,000 --> 00:10:32,000
And probably the reason for that was that, you know, I'm from Memphis. And so my grandmother had told me all these horror stories about Mississippi.

65
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:45,000
So Mississippi meant something to me in a way that say Albany didn't. Because all my life, you know, my grandmother's thing was don't ever go to Mississippi.

66
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:49,000
It's the worst of the worst for black people.

67
00:10:49,000 --> 00:10:50,000
Yeah.

68
00:10:50,000 --> 00:11:01,000
When you did finally bump right up against the expulsion threat and then survive it just barely.

69
00:11:01,000 --> 00:11:07,000
But then confront that decision about taking the further plunge. How did you, many are young person, you're very young person.

70
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:11,000
How did you find your way across that terrain?

71
00:11:11,000 --> 00:11:15,000
I do not know.

72
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:25,000
I wonder, you know, because it just, I don't know how I did it really.

73
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:36,000
I think certainly the models of the other students who had done it and survived death and brutality.

74
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:50,000
But I found it interesting that Vincent Harding and his project where they filmed me and all and they called it answering the call.

75
00:11:50,000 --> 00:11:56,000
And I guess that's what happened even though I never, these were not my words.

76
00:11:56,000 --> 00:12:06,000
But I definitely was, I was very conflicted. But yet could not go, I couldn't pull back.

77
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:21,000
Even though I wanted to so badly because the life that I had planned for myself, I thought I was going to lose it, you know, going to college, getting a degree.

78
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:30,000
Being able to live a middle class life, you know, with a nice home, a car, those things that I'd never had.

79
00:12:30,000 --> 00:12:38,000
But then, you know, somebody like Willie "Mukasa" Ricks, you know, would say, I don't care how many degrees you've got, you know.

80
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:44,000
You're still going to be, you know, the the n-word, no matter what.

81
00:12:44,000 --> 00:12:49,000
Ph.D., no D. It won't make a difference, you know.

82
00:12:49,000 --> 00:12:54,000
And of course, I knew that there was truth there, you know.

83
00:12:54,000 --> 00:13:01,000
Even though I knew I wanted what that could bring me. I don't know why I couldn't walk away.

84
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:19,000
Can you describe the, the, the, I guess I'll say what may have been kind of an emotional and psychological challenge of confronting the prospect of going to Mississippi in 64.

85
00:13:20,000 --> 00:13:40,000
Yeah, that, um, and since I've, you know, talked about it and written about it, I have not been able to, uh, relive or remember, um, how I was able to decide I was going to do that.

86
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:59,000
You know, I remember how frightened I was of going, the actual driving from Ohio into Mississippi with my two colleagues who had been assigned to Laurel Mississippi along with myself.

87
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:17,000
And I know that having been a part of the planning of the, uh, Freedom Summer primarily through working with Dr. Lind, who was working on the Freedom School curriculum.

88
00:14:17,000 --> 00:14:25,000
And I had taken a second class with him and was working with him on that for my project.

89
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:30,000
So that, and I said, I want to be a Freedom School teacher, you know.

90
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:46,000
Uh, so that really had me and then just being on the, um, coordinating committee and hearing the plans and meeting Bob Moses and really getting to know a number of the Mississippi staff and the plans.

91
00:14:46,000 --> 00:14:58,000
And I think the main reason that I thought we might survive was because of the white students who were going to be going, you know, a thousand.

92
00:14:58,000 --> 00:15:03,000
And I was like, they're not going to kill them, you know.

93
00:15:03,000 --> 00:15:21,000
Uh, so that'll give us some protection. So of course, that was shattered, uh, you know, because before I left the second week of the orientation, uh, three, the three Mississippi workers had disappeared and two of them were white.

94
00:15:21,000 --> 00:15:33,000
And when we were called in to the, uh, a plenary where we were told this and Bob said they are probably dead.

95
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:46,000
I just, I couldn't believe it. I was like dead. I mean, you know, because I had met, uh, James Chaney, uh, that first week.

96
00:15:46,000 --> 00:15:59,000
And it was like, oh, these people really will kill us. I mean, it was like, even whites, they will kill whites, you know, white males.

97
00:15:59,000 --> 00:16:10,000
It was so that definitely, um, made me say, oh, we really could lose our lives here. This is, this is no joke, you know.

98
00:16:10,000 --> 00:16:22,000
And so then I get assigned to Laurel Mississippi with two other black people because it's too dangerous to send whites into Laurel.

99
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:33,000
Well, that, that just, I thought, oh my god, but I thought that was the whole plan, you know, to have middle class whites and some other class.

100
00:16:33,000 --> 00:16:41,000
Um, that's going to bring some help, you know, the government is not going to let this happen, the federal government.

101
00:16:41,000 --> 00:16:44,000
They're going to send people in there to protect us, you know.

102
00:16:44,000 --> 00:17:02,000
So I just, when I went, um, with my two colleagues, uh, James "Jimmy" Garrett, as we call him James "Jimmy" Garrett and, um, Lester McKinney, I just thought, we're never going to get out out of here alive, you know.

103
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:21,000
But we've got to go. And I think in my case, the fact that I had severed my ties with my family, I didn't feel like I could go back home and would just be terrible to admit that I was wrong.

104
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:25,000
And, you know, so it was, I had to go forward.

105
00:17:25,000 --> 00:17:42,000
Was part of the, um, well, let me ask you this way, to what extent was, um, was your Christian faith at that point, one of the mechanisms for accommodating and encountering all that fear?

106
00:17:42,000 --> 00:17:48,000
I don't remember it being, uh, a support for me at that point.

107
00:17:48,000 --> 00:17:57,000
It did, it developed later. And it's so funny. You mentioned that because we talked about that in the class. I teach on the civil rights and religion.

108
00:17:57,000 --> 00:18:13,000
Um, I think once there and living in the community and of course, you know, we had to go to church and we had to participate in a lot of the local community church related activities.

109
00:18:13,000 --> 00:18:23,000
It's as if I redeveloped faith that I think drawing from the faith of the local people.

110
00:18:23,000 --> 00:18:52,000
Um, that's when I remember it kicking back in, uh, even though I had been raised, you know, in the church and with very devout parents and grandparents and all, I don't remember drawing on that until I actually was in the state and living with the family and, and seeing their faith, I think I drew on their faith to bolster my own.

111
00:18:52,000 --> 00:19:00,000
Can you, um, first you can recall your initial pattern of impression of, uh, volume city?

112
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:12,000
Well, I think I've mentioned in something I wrote that at one point when, because the way that I was able to go, I slept the whole way from Ohio.

113
00:19:12,000 --> 00:19:20,000
Uh, and I couldn't drive so I was in the backseat and the two men were in the front and they were switching off the driving.

114
00:19:20,000 --> 00:19:33,000
And when we stopped, I'd say, are we there yet, you know, and they say, no, we're not, you know, but at the point that I recall, uh, waking up and they said, you're in Mississippi.

115
00:19:33,000 --> 00:19:43,000
And I was like, I don't know, this is crazy, but I don't know why I expected it to look different from the rest of the country.

116
00:19:43,000 --> 00:19:53,000
And I said, oh, it doesn't look different, you know, I don't know what I thought monsters would be swinging from trees or something.

117
00:19:53,000 --> 00:20:00,000
But we weren't able to go directly to Laurel because we didn't have any structure there.

118
00:20:00,000 --> 00:20:12,000
So we went to Hattiesburg, Mississippi, which was one of the best organized, uh, communities in Mississippi, ready for the movement workers and all.

119
00:20:12,000 --> 00:20:23,000
And so what we did was to, you know, get assigned places to live, but the three of us would drive the 30 miles north to Laurel.

120
00:20:23,000 --> 00:20:34,000
And we had some names and we started knocking on doors and telling people who we were, et cetera, trying to find a base of operations.

121
00:20:34,000 --> 00:20:35,000
And...

122
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:42,000
You've written in a way that I remember very vividly and I'd like to have you tell a story again of going up the doors and speaking stuff.

123
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:45,000
Yeah, and Mrs. Eberhart Spinks.

124
00:20:45,000 --> 00:20:52,000
Yes, she was on our list and, um, when I knocked on her door and she opened it.

125
00:20:52,000 --> 00:21:01,000
Um, and I was, you know, I had on what I think was the uniform, you know, the blue jeans, the blue jean,

126
00:21:01,000 --> 00:21:08,000
the Yorkshire condom thing. And I went to say, my name is, you know, Gwen Robinson.

127
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:13,000
And she said, are you one of those Freedom Riders?

128
00:21:13,000 --> 00:21:23,000
And I was like, oh, is that good or bad? I said, yes, ma'am. And she said, come in. I've been waiting on you all my life.

129
00:21:23,000 --> 00:21:32,000
And that was the beginning of the Laurel Project. It just took off. She was a dynamic person.

130
00:21:32,000 --> 00:21:40,000
And she was like, when I went on to tell her what we had planned and the freedom schools and all of that.

131
00:21:40,000 --> 00:21:45,000
She said, oh, yeah, oh, yeah, I'm forward. I'm forward. I've been waiting.

132
00:21:45,000 --> 00:21:52,000
You can stay with me. And I said, well, I've got two guys, you know, and she says, I'll get my neighbor to put them up.

133
00:21:52,000 --> 00:22:02,000
And that was Mrs. Carrie Clayton, who lived across the street. She said, y'all can go back to Haddishburg and get your things and come on back.

134
00:22:02,000 --> 00:22:08,000
And that's exactly what we did. And that was the beginning of the Laurel Project.

135
00:22:08,000 --> 00:22:21,000
Two combination of factors motivated those two women in their specific circumstances, personal and material to extend that invitation to the freedom.

136
00:22:22,000 --> 00:22:36,000
That's a good question. Mrs. Eberhart Spinks and I mean, the two ladies were not alike at all. First of all, I would say that Mrs. Clayton was at least 20 years older.

137
00:22:36,000 --> 00:22:47,000
She was an older lady. A widow had quite a lovely home. And I mean, she was putting a lot on the line to let us move in there.

138
00:22:48,000 --> 00:23:01,000
But Mrs. Eberhart Spinks was a fighter. I mean, she was like, I'm sick and tired of this. You know, it's time for this to change.

139
00:23:01,000 --> 00:23:15,000
Mrs. Clayton didn't talk very much. They were friends. They were neighbors. Had been for years. But it was, as I was trying to recall, Mrs. Clayton lived.

140
00:23:15,000 --> 00:23:31,000
Mrs. Eberhart Spinks knew the talking. And she just nod her head and smile. But they were so gracious to us. You know, they just opened their homes. Now Mrs. Eberhart Spinks's husband, he was worried as he should be.

141
00:23:31,000 --> 00:23:39,000
But he worked at Masonite Corporation plant there in Laurel and he was in a union.

142
00:23:39,000 --> 00:23:53,000
So this otherwise, I mean, he would have lost his job, you know. But rightfully so, he was not nearly as supportive. She just was like, we're doing this. We're doing this.

143
00:23:53,000 --> 00:24:02,000
And I didn't think he liked it so much initially, you know. But she was the driving force.

144
00:24:02,000 --> 00:24:05,000
How old was she?

145
00:24:05,000 --> 00:24:18,000
I'd say late 40s, early 50s. She had a son. Yeah. She had a son in the house. Yes. Other children were grown and had left.

146
00:24:18,000 --> 00:24:29,000
He was about 13 to 14. And that was another thing that was a little scary, you know, for him. What might happen to him, you know.

147
00:24:29,000 --> 00:24:43,000
But the minute we let the people in Jackson and Atlanta know, folks started being sent in, you know. We wound up with, I believe, 23 volunteers.

148
00:24:43,000 --> 00:24:52,000
And so they helped us get housing for them. And, you know, we were often running very quickly.

149
00:24:52,000 --> 00:25:03,000
And let me have you talk about that the summer of active, all the things that you said in motion, but, but true, maybe through the lens of the leadership role that very quickly.

150
00:25:03,000 --> 00:25:05,000
Yeah. Right.

151
00:25:05,000 --> 00:25:13,000
Yeah, it was. Listen, that is exactly the right way because I went there to be the Freedom School teacher.

152
00:25:13,000 --> 00:25:22,000
And Lester McKinney was the season's Nick Worker. He had been to Mississippi. He had been to jail, you know.

153
00:25:22,000 --> 00:25:29,000
I mean, real, you know, I had been locked up in Atlanta, but nothing compared to what Lester had been through already.

154
00:25:29,000 --> 00:25:39,000
So Lester disappeared. And, you know, anytime someone didn't show up, it was terror time, you know.

155
00:25:39,000 --> 00:25:47,000
So, of course, I was calling Jackson and Atlanta, you know, they got right on the horn to the US Justice Department FBI, et cetera.

156
00:25:47,000 --> 00:26:04,000
And we didn't hear from him for a couple of days. And then they threw, I don't know, I don't remember if it was the COFO office in Jackson, but clearly everybody, the alert had gone out.

157
00:26:04,000 --> 00:26:10,000
And it was discovered that he had been picked up and he was in the lock up there.

158
00:26:10,000 --> 00:26:20,000
And I can't believe even to this day that he didn't tell anybody that he had been arrested the last time he had been in Jones County, Mississippi.

159
00:26:20,000 --> 00:26:27,000
And he had not gone back for his hearing to pay the fine. So they picked him up on an old charge.

160
00:26:27,000 --> 00:26:39,000
And it was very difficult to get him out of the county. And the only way was that he had to sign an affidavit that he would not come back for five years.

161
00:26:39,000 --> 00:26:43,000
Or he was going to do some real time.

162
00:26:43,000 --> 00:26:51,000
That left James "Jimmy" Garrett, who was from California, had never been south in his life and myself.

163
00:26:51,000 --> 00:26:57,000
And I think I don't think we even had any of the other volunteers at that point. It was just the two of us.

164
00:26:57,000 --> 00:27:07,000
It happened very quickly. And so when James Forman calls me and says, you've got to step up. I'm trying to find somebody to send.

165
00:27:07,000 --> 00:27:14,000
But we don't have anybody right now. Everybody's tied up. So we need you to become the project director.

166
00:27:14,000 --> 00:27:20,000
Well, I thought this has got to be a joke. I mean, say you're from the South. You've been to jail.

167
00:27:20,000 --> 00:27:29,000
I was like, yeah, but I don't know anything about organizing. You know, this is, he says, well, it will send somebody.

168
00:27:29,000 --> 00:27:39,000
Don't worry. Somebody will be there soon to relieve you. And nobody ever was sent to relieve me. And I wound up staying 16 months.

169
00:27:39,000 --> 00:27:45,000
Yeah, some of your impressions of.

170
00:27:45,000 --> 00:27:52,000
We'll stop for a moment. Okay, we're back after a short break to get a little drink water.

171
00:27:52,000 --> 00:28:04,000
Dr. Simple, let me ask about how you gathered yourself up and began to take charge in a SNCC leadership kind of way.

172
00:28:04,000 --> 00:28:11,000
Context, however, your model was. Can you tell me about that? With this band of students come into the county.

173
00:28:11,000 --> 00:28:27,000
Yeah, you know, it's unfortunate that I wish photographic memory where I could just pull back those scenes.

174
00:28:27,000 --> 00:28:35,000
There are some scenes that I have often where we were having a great laugh or at a church or something.

175
00:28:35,000 --> 00:28:42,000
But I have no idea how on earth I was able to do that.

176
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:55,000
I really now, I guess I must say that having been brought up in a church where I played a leadership role taught to.

177
00:28:55,000 --> 00:29:05,000
But in my high school, you know, I was editor of the school paper. I was the president of our high school sorority.

178
00:29:05,000 --> 00:29:12,000
I was the president of my Girl Scout troop because I remained a Girl Scout until I graduated from high school.

179
00:29:12,000 --> 00:29:14,000
You're elected by your person. Yes.

180
00:29:14,000 --> 00:29:25,000
Exactly. So, you know, all of this had prepared me, but little did I know that, you know, because I never would have thought.

181
00:29:25,000 --> 00:29:36,000
But, you know, so organizing, I had been brought up and had done that from an early age, you know.

182
00:29:36,000 --> 00:29:47,000
So, once the shock of it all and then, you know, when they would call us and tell us to a showing up at the bus stop, get somebody down there to pick them up, you know.

183
00:29:47,000 --> 00:29:51,000
So, they won't be standing around somebody or spot them, you know.

184
00:29:51,000 --> 00:29:57,000
It just, it sort of started happening, you know. We got to organize.

185
00:29:57,000 --> 00:30:07,000
And then it's, it's living with Miss Finks. She being the leader and I'm living in the house with her.

186
00:30:07,000 --> 00:30:23,000
And she was, even though she wasn't as old as my grandmother, she reminded me of her, you know, so active in her church and so active in her community, the NAACP chapter there and all.

187
00:30:23,000 --> 00:30:31,000
You had grown up in your grandmother's home. Exactly. It's seeing the same kind of thing, you know, my folks, because in Memphis, they could vote.

188
00:30:31,000 --> 00:30:40,000
And my grandmother and grandfather, they were always trying to get people registered to vote. So, I had seen that, you know.

189
00:30:40,000 --> 00:30:59,000
And even with the terrible Jim Crow that we had there, the, even though blacks did not run for office until much later in my high school life, they would come to the black churches to campaign.

190
00:30:59,000 --> 00:31:15,000
So, I had seen that and so, you know, there was some sense of how you organize this stuff, you know. But when they told me, it seemed to me like, I'm not prepared because, you know, I just saw it as so different.

191
00:31:15,000 --> 00:31:21,000
But those skills just came to the floor, you know.

192
00:31:21,000 --> 00:31:35,000
What emerged in that summer in terms of the range of projects you set in motion, Freedom School of Registration, NFDP?

193
00:31:35,000 --> 00:31:45,000
Does any part of that work stand out in some distinct way against your memory against the other?

194
00:31:45,000 --> 00:31:56,000
Well, first of all, you know, we really had a great group. And I think that's probably true for every site.

195
00:31:56,000 --> 00:32:10,000
But, you know, just thinking back about those volunteers, you know, how they just came in there and rolled up their sleeves and, you know, got to work.

196
00:32:10,000 --> 00:32:31,000
We had great difficulty initially getting an office. So, our first office was on Mrs. Clayton's back porch. And when it rained, we'd have to run inside with the mimeograph machine and all about papers and typewriter and stuff, and go into her living room and set up shop there.

197
00:32:31,000 --> 00:32:43,000
But we finally got this man to rent a black man, a wealthy man, who had had a nightclub that was closed down in terrible shape.

198
00:32:43,000 --> 00:32:59,000
Finally got him to an exorbitant price. And, you know, just remembering how the people in the community and how we all went in there pretty much made that place.

199
00:32:59,000 --> 00:33:07,000
And, you know, putting windows in and causing it to have been boarded up. It was in terrible shape, you know.

200
00:33:07,000 --> 00:33:16,000
So, the community just turned out it was like a barn raising kind of thing. That just, you know, was a wonderful thing.

201
00:33:16,000 --> 00:33:26,000
And, of course, it was terrible that it was fire bombed and destroyed. But, while it was once we fixed it up, there were offices.

202
00:33:26,000 --> 00:33:33,000
We held the Freedom School there. We had a library there. So, that was such a wonderful thing.

203
00:33:33,000 --> 00:33:41,000
We also had some young women who wanted to set up what was called a Freedom Nursery School.

204
00:33:41,000 --> 00:33:47,000
So, not only did we have a Freedom School that taught, you know, first through 12th.

205
00:33:47,000 --> 00:33:54,000
And then we started doing literacy for adults in the evenings.

206
00:33:54,000 --> 00:34:18,000
That was just wonderful. Also, though, the mock voter registration project that we launched all across the state, where people actually came to the offices to register in a mock to show that if blacks had been given the privilege they would.

207
00:34:18,000 --> 00:34:27,000
The organizing of the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party chapter. And, seeing how the people just took that and ran with it.

208
00:34:27,000 --> 00:34:41,000
So, I think there was so many wonderful things that just let me, I mean, that shaped my life and my whole sense of what people can do.

209
00:34:41,000 --> 00:34:50,000
People with not a lot of formal education. But, once they catch it, they run with it.

210
00:34:50,000 --> 00:34:57,000
And that's what happened. They were running with it. And so, were we many times trying to keep up with them, you know.

211
00:34:57,000 --> 00:35:08,000
So, I just have a wonderful overall memory of that period. I think is being one of the most important in my life.

212
00:35:08,000 --> 00:35:28,000
Let me point to a couple of things on the calendar of those that near horizon after your arrival, those through the summer months that were of course very difficult to discover the confirmation of the deaths of the disappearance of Goodman, Chaney, and Schwerner (June 21, 1964).

213
00:35:28,000 --> 00:35:39,000
And then different, different episode, but also a very serious matter, the Atlantic City MFDP delegation challenge.

214
00:35:39,000 --> 00:36:00,000
I wonder kind of how you were evaluating both your project in a narrow term and moral and the wider effort against circumstances like those.

215
00:36:00,000 --> 00:36:16,000
Well, you know, I did not go with our group. I certainly was very involved in getting our group ready. And then we went to Jackson where we had the state convention. And then that's where the delegates were picked.

216
00:36:16,000 --> 00:36:29,000
And we had two people from Laurel to go as a part of the state delegation. And, you know, just the disappointment of what happened there.

217
00:36:29,000 --> 00:36:42,000
Because I know the people and I too, you know, we thought that we would be seated, you know, we just couldn't believe because we were naive, you know, about the political system.

218
00:36:42,000 --> 00:36:58,000
And didn't understand, you know, the President Johnson was going to throw us under the bus as they now say in order to keep the dems, the regulars in his camp.

219
00:36:58,000 --> 00:37:20,000
You know, we didn't know how this whole thing worked. You know, that had a profound effect on all of us. And I think it certainly affected the SNCC workers, the season SNCC workers. And jaded us in some ways, you know, because it's like politics over people.

220
00:37:20,000 --> 00:37:32,000
Even when people are dying to do this, still politics was elevated. And I think that jaded a lot of us.

221
00:37:32,000 --> 00:37:42,000
Yeah. How do you think your way through the very difficult question of stay on or not at the end of the summer?

222
00:37:42,000 --> 00:37:53,000
That too, you know, when you try to think back now that people are interviewing me about it, I try to say, wow, how did you make that decision?

223
00:37:53,000 --> 00:38:06,000
Because of course, a Staughton Lynd had helped me to get into Antioch College. And in fact, I drove to Ohio with Storten on my way to the orientation.

224
00:38:06,000 --> 00:38:23,000
And we stopped at Antioch College for me to have my interview because it had, you know, and all been paperwork and Dr. Lynn had gotten Coretta Scott King to write me a letter of recommendation.

225
00:38:24,000 --> 00:38:40,000
So, you know, I was headed to Antioch College. I wasn't even going back to Spelman. But I just couldn't leave Mrs. Eberhart Spinks, Mrs. Clayton, Mr. Richardson, all those wonderful people.

226
00:38:41,000 --> 00:38:53,000
It was almost like, wow, we're just getting started. We can't all leave and just couldn't do it.

227
00:38:53,000 --> 00:39:01,000
And so I wrote a letter and Antioch College was very gracious. And they said, oh yeah, no problem. You know, your scholarship will be here in January.

228
00:39:02,000 --> 00:39:11,000
So that made it easier. And then two other women said they'd stay with me, which made it easier. I wasn't staying by myself.

229
00:39:11,000 --> 00:39:29,000
And it just so happened that the three of us all lived with Mrs. Eberhart Spinks. So she had taken two others in. And so, Lynelle Barrett and, oh my goodness, Marion Davidson, both from California.

230
00:39:29,000 --> 00:39:39,000
So we stayed on and we shared our bedroom there, the three of us, for another year.

231
00:39:39,000 --> 00:39:40,000
Yeah.

232
00:39:40,000 --> 00:39:46,000
We're back on that for your short break.

233
00:39:47,000 --> 00:40:00,000
I'm interested to have you reflect a little bit about the leader you became in that crucible of very complex circumstances.

234
00:40:00,000 --> 00:40:20,000
And have you talked a little bit also on that theme of the extent to which maybe in a more self-conscious way you began to think of yourself now as project director, a leader organizer?

235
00:40:20,000 --> 00:40:46,000
That's a good point. I'm not sure when I might have begun thinking of myself in that way. I think I've written some place that when I looked back without knowing it that I had a feminist way of organizing in the sense of I was not for top down.

236
00:40:46,000 --> 00:40:51,000
I mean, you just had to be life and death.

237
00:40:51,000 --> 00:41:01,000
But then, Snick was a very ultra-democratic.

238
00:41:01,000 --> 00:41:12,000
So probably that helped a lot. And so in our, in the project, we discussed everything. You know, sometimes we like Snick before me.

239
00:41:12,000 --> 00:41:19,000
We'd meet for hours coming to decisions. And that seemed right to me, you know.

240
00:41:19,000 --> 00:41:35,000
And so that form of leadership that's where everybody has to say, you try to come to consensus as opposed to just the vote unless you just cannot reach consensus.

241
00:41:35,000 --> 00:41:51,000
And we realized that that was my way up. Let's try to reach a consensus on these things. Because all of our lives on the line and this project, these people, you know, we can hop a greyhound and go home, but they're at home.

242
00:41:51,000 --> 00:41:58,000
So everything we do is so important, so critical.

243
00:41:58,000 --> 00:42:12,000
And then also just being a woman, you know, I often had to struggle around issues related to a woman being a project director.

244
00:42:12,000 --> 00:42:18,000
As I learned, I think there were three of us in Mississippi that summer.

245
00:42:18,000 --> 00:42:26,000
And it was, we had to fight for the resources, you know, we had to fight to get a good car.

246
00:42:26,000 --> 00:42:38,000
Because the guys would get first dibs on everything and that wasn't fair. So that was another battle with Jackson over distribution of cars and good typewriters.

247
00:42:38,000 --> 00:42:50,000
So, you know, it was a struggle and to be taken seriously by the leadership as well as by your male colleagues.

248
00:42:50,000 --> 00:42:56,000
And the race factor also was a big one.

249
00:42:56,000 --> 00:43:08,000
You know, I'm from Memphis. I'd been brought up in the total segregation until I met Storden and some of the other white professors.

250
00:43:08,000 --> 00:43:25,000
I'd never had a relationship of equals, you know. So here was a tremendous thing. So standing up to these white young men who were my age and a few years older, you know, from Stanford, from Yale.

251
00:43:25,000 --> 00:43:35,000
I mean, you know, we even had a good year. And I mean, of the good year tired rubber company, one of our volunteers, you know.

252
00:43:35,000 --> 00:43:45,000
So there was class, there was race and gender issues, just swirling, you know.

253
00:43:45,000 --> 00:43:59,000
And one of the things that we often don't talk about, but, you know, there was a sexual harassment that often happened toward the women.

254
00:43:59,000 --> 00:44:08,000
And so there was one of the things that, you know, I took a stand on that. This was not, we're not going to get a consensus on this.

255
00:44:08,000 --> 00:44:16,000
There is not going to be sexual harassment of any of the women on this project or any of the women in this community.

256
00:44:16,000 --> 00:44:20,000
And you will be put out if you do it.

257
00:44:20,000 --> 00:44:28,000
I bet in that's really interesting point. I bet in those at that time, I bet you didn't use the phrase sexual.

258
00:44:28,000 --> 00:44:31,000
No. What would the language have been? I'm wondering.

259
00:44:31,000 --> 00:44:35,000
What would it have been for you to make that point then?

260
00:44:35,000 --> 00:44:45,000
That's a good question, you know, it's like, you know, guys, you cannot force a woman to do anything that she doesn't want to do on this project, you know.

261
00:44:45,000 --> 00:44:54,000
Because I had seen a little of that at the orientation. And I had seen it prior to going to the orientation.

262
00:44:54,000 --> 00:45:03,000
I had a strong arming woman. And I was furious, you know, because here we are.

263
00:45:03,000 --> 00:45:15,000
And I had, you know, had my own situation that happened to me there. And someone whom I trusted and thought, you know, I looked up to.

264
00:45:15,000 --> 00:45:18,000
And I was sexually assaulted.

265
00:45:18,000 --> 00:45:24,000
So here's like, oh my God, you know, we're going into the lion's den.

266
00:45:24,000 --> 00:45:28,000
And we've got to be worried about our comrades.

267
00:45:28,000 --> 00:45:32,000
You know, that was a no, no. That was an absolute no no.

268
00:45:32,000 --> 00:45:38,000
Is project director in that context, could you on your authority? Could you have dismissed someone?

269
00:45:38,000 --> 00:45:46,000
I sure thought I could. And I said I would. I mean, they probably would have been sent to Jackson and had to go somewhere else.

270
00:45:46,000 --> 00:45:56,000
But an absolute flat no. You know, you are not doing that on this project.

271
00:45:56,000 --> 00:46:11,000
And maybe you have, I don't know. If you were, if someone were to talk with those volunteers who came to Laurel and to ask them about what made you so effective.

272
00:46:11,000 --> 00:46:19,000
I know this kind of self-congratulatory question I'm posing that it's a ask you that answer. But, but what do you think they would have said?

273
00:46:19,000 --> 00:46:22,000
Produced that.

274
00:46:22,000 --> 00:46:38,000
It's interesting. One of these Nick volunteers from Stanford. And I have recently, I, well, we sort of connected maybe 20, so our years ago. And now we've reconnected.

275
00:46:38,000 --> 00:46:50,000
And he just sent me something I'm so happy to have because I have no documents from this period. He sent me a letter that I wrote while I was still in Laurel.

276
00:46:50,000 --> 00:46:59,000
I mean, I treasure that. I want to make sure that it's already, you know, very fragile. So it has to be preserved by me.

277
00:46:59,000 --> 00:47:12,000
But I don't know what they would say. That's a good question. I can tell you what I hope they would say. I hope they would say that I was fair.

278
00:47:12,000 --> 00:47:27,000
And since the year and trying to help us all to stay alive and to keep our community people alive and not lose their property.

279
00:47:27,000 --> 00:47:38,000
But I can give you his name and number and email address you can ask him since we're now communicating.

280
00:47:38,000 --> 00:47:55,000
And standing on where there are times. What were the, what were the very worst things you bumped up against in terms of the prospect of white violence? You mentioned, of course, and I know that the, that the communities that the, what had become the freedom house was fire bomb.

281
00:47:55,000 --> 00:48:09,000
Yes, it was fire bomb. We had, and that was, you know, during the time when we had the large number of us. No, that happened after that actual summer.

282
00:48:09,000 --> 00:48:25,000
Then we, I'm getting a bit confused. We had two high school age young men who were sent to Laurel after the bulk of the volunteers left.

283
00:48:25,000 --> 00:48:41,000
Ulysses Everett and Charles, we call them Ben, Ben Hartfield from Hattiesburg. They had been kicked out of the public school.

284
00:48:41,000 --> 00:48:55,000
And they were sent to Laurel to work with us. And another local, Mississippi, and from the Delta named John Handy.

285
00:48:55,000 --> 00:49:12,000
So we were a project of six with two high school age young people, John was more close and age to us, but had not had much schooling. In fact, was illiterate.

286
00:49:12,000 --> 00:49:21,000
And so we went on now.

287
00:49:21,000 --> 00:49:28,000
Those, yes, those guys, but the women are white women. Yes, yes.

288
00:49:28,000 --> 00:49:46,000
The, after, you know, it was very hard for us to find another place that would rent to us. But we were able to secure another office, but it wasn't anything like what we had created there.

289
00:49:46,000 --> 00:50:03,000
And it was a part of a duplex. So people lived next door. It was one of these three room shotgun places. We sort of got it without telling the folk who we really were. And Ben and Ulysses lived in there.

290
00:50:03,000 --> 00:50:15,000
And that place was fire bombed also, which was, I mean, just unbelievable because there was a man and his wife and children in the other side.

291
00:50:15,000 --> 00:50:33,000
And you know, as everybody down there said, it was an act of God because when they put the Molotov cocktail or whatever the device was, instead of it blowing the house up, it blew the gas line away from the house.

292
00:50:34,000 --> 00:50:44,000
And so the explosion really, I mean, the house did catch on fire that side of it, but people were able to get out.

293
00:50:44,000 --> 00:50:58,000
And we basically kept that place as our workplace, even with the burns and the person who owned it didn't repair it. Thank goodness the damage was done on our side.

294
00:50:59,000 --> 00:51:13,000
And so that was a shock, you know, there was a joke. And then we started working on desegregation there in Laurel trying to integrate some of the little restaurants and things.

295
00:51:13,000 --> 00:51:27,000
And people went to jail and, you know, we had a few marches. So we really expanded out while keeping the freedom school going on the weekends, because kids were in school at night.

296
00:51:27,000 --> 00:51:45,000
We would do literacy training. We were still organizing for the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party. So there was slow times, you know, when things slowed up after all the people left, you know. But we carried on.

297
00:51:45,000 --> 00:51:54,000
Was there any compliance in the county around Laurel on public combinations front? No. No, exactly.

298
00:51:54,000 --> 00:52:07,000
And that's what I think was infuriated people, you know. Jones County, Mississippi, you know, had a big clan base there. So it was dangerous.

299
00:52:07,000 --> 00:52:19,000
Yeah. Did you have to navigate and have strategies for interacting with local, say, the sheriff? Did you yourself kind of bump up against the sheriff?

300
00:52:19,000 --> 00:52:43,000
Yes, I did. In fact, I don't I think somewhere I know I've told this story. I led a little group of primarily high school age students in one of the efforts to desegregate one of the little restaurants and the sheriff came and pulled the gun and threatened me.

301
00:52:43,000 --> 00:53:03,000
And I just kept leading my little group on past him and he laughed and he cursed and he said, you know, you're going to get your it's so-and-so and self-killed and put his gun back in his holster. That is past.

302
00:53:03,000 --> 00:53:27,000
So, you know, it was just an amazing thing, you know, and then Ulysses and Ben on another occasion led a group and they were arrested and then we led our little group down there to stand outside the jail and sing to them, you know, freedom songs and we got pushed around, but we didn't they didn't lock the kids up.

303
00:53:27,000 --> 00:53:50,000
You know, so we had a few things like that. In retrospect, I think we did pretty good that we didn't get injured more. I mean, it was property, you know, that they went after burning crosses and trying to frighten the people, threatening the ministers that their churches would be burned if they kept letting us use the churches, you know, things of that nature.

304
00:53:50,000 --> 00:54:10,000
Mrs. Fink's on more than one occasion had to, you know, talk about boycotting a church to make the church open back up to us, you know, it was like this is our church and you're not going to shut out our movement people, you know, this is our church, you know, she fought battles in the black community.

305
00:54:10,000 --> 00:54:29,000
You know, the churches were, you know, the prize possessions, you know, but sometimes those ministers were scared and they were displaced by all these new movement leaders taking over.

306
00:54:29,000 --> 00:54:42,000
They had been the ones going downtown with hand in hand, you know, and now we were going around them to making demands that they would never have demanded, you know.

307
00:54:42,000 --> 00:54:52,000
So sometimes they didn't like it, not only were they afraid for their churches, but they didn't like being displaced as the leaders, you know.

308
00:54:52,000 --> 00:55:02,000
Let me turn the conversation in the direction of Atlanta and you were turned to SNCC and Atlanta.

309
00:55:02,000 --> 00:55:21,000
And the very, very big and complex question of how coming out of those kinds of experiences and transitioning through 65 into 66 say, you and others are really beginning fundamentally to rethink the model that should,

310
00:55:21,000 --> 00:55:31,000
the movement should be organized around the philosophy theory of the movement, maybe with the goals and objectives now should be reconceptualized as something new and different.

311
00:55:31,000 --> 00:55:54,000
Yeah, you know, it's interesting, James Forman was responsible for me leaving Mississippi because he recognized that I was, what do we call it now when these guys come back from Iraq and Shells, no, you know, they have another term.

312
00:55:54,000 --> 00:56:12,000
Yes, what happened was just to back up a little bit, we had a very large demonstration in Jackson at the Capitol and I think a thousand of us were arrested.

313
00:56:12,000 --> 00:56:20,000
This was toward the end of my time there, even though I did not know it at that time, I had no intention of leaving.

314
00:56:20,000 --> 00:56:32,000
But I was arrested with this thousand people, so many, you know, they didn't know what in the world they were going to do with this, so what they did was to take us to the Mississippi State Fairgrounds.

315
00:56:32,000 --> 00:56:52,000
And we were put in the houses that had, they normally used for livestock and I spent 15 days there and it was, we were brutalized very badly, lots of beatings and all kinds of terrorizing.

316
00:56:52,000 --> 00:57:15,000
So when I got out, I had two car accidents that were my fault, head on just, you know, and at that point, Jim said, what happened? And I said, I don't know, I mean, I destroyed two cars in two weeks.

317
00:57:15,000 --> 00:57:25,000
He said, you got to come out, it's something wrong with you, you know. And I said, but I can't leave. He said, well, what good are you going to be to those people in Laurel?

318
00:57:25,000 --> 00:57:35,000
If you either kill yourself in a car accident or something's wrong, just, you don't have to stay, but I want you to come to New York.

319
00:57:35,000 --> 00:57:46,000
And I worked with the Friends of SNCC, so I went to New York with the promise that I was going back to Laurel.

320
00:57:46,000 --> 00:58:00,000
And it's just so amazing because I was only in New York about three months and I worked with the Friends of SNCC organizing out of the New York Snick office.

321
00:58:00,000 --> 00:58:14,000
But it was three months that on my own time, I sort of really found out about the nation of Islam.

322
00:58:14,000 --> 00:58:25,000
And even though Malcolm was dead, but just that whole notion that blacks needed their own land in this country, we deserved it.

323
00:58:25,000 --> 00:58:39,000
I mean, that whole idea, which was totally foreign to me, you know. And then I lived in Harlem and those preachers standing out on the corner, 160th and 7th.

324
00:58:39,000 --> 00:58:46,000
I started hearing stuff I'd never heard in my life, you know, of black nationalists.

325
00:58:46,000 --> 00:58:59,000
I also met and started going to the Black Arts Theatre with LeRoi Jones.

326
00:58:59,000 --> 00:59:17,000
So those three months, you know, had a profound impact on me in terms of, hey, there's a whole another thought process about what black folks need to do that's not about integration, which I didn't know anything about, you know.

327
00:59:17,000 --> 00:59:29,000
So, okay, that happens. But then Julian Bond is elected, duly elected and not permitted to take his seat in the Georgia State Legislature.

328
00:59:29,000 --> 00:59:42,000
And James Forman asked me if I would come back, but not to Mississippi, but to Atlanta to help organize his re-election campaign.

329
00:59:42,000 --> 00:59:52,000
So that's how I got to Atlanta, but I've had three months of hearing a whole nother song I've never heard before, you know.

330
00:59:52,000 --> 00:59:55,000
And you teriel that back into the offices at SNCC?

331
00:59:55,000 --> 00:59:57,000
Yes, I do.

332
00:59:57,000 --> 00:59:58,000
Where there were other people.

333
00:59:58,000 --> 01:00:13,000
I mean, I mean, Michael Simmons, my former husband, who did grow up with knowledge of the nation from Philadelphia?

334
01:00:13,000 --> 01:00:19,000
His brother was the National Secretary [of the Nation of Islam].

335
01:00:19,000 --> 01:00:28,000
And he before he and Malcolm X married, they shared an apartment.

336
01:00:28,000 --> 01:00:33,000
And so my ex-husband had no Malcolm X.

337
01:00:33,000 --> 01:00:49,000
Yeah. So, Michael had come to Atlanta as a part of the delegation from Arkansas for a SNCC meeting.

338
01:00:49,000 --> 01:00:56,000
I recruited him to come to work with getting Julian re-elected.

339
01:00:56,000 --> 01:01:07,000
Also, another person who was his best friend from Philadelphia, Dwight Williams.

340
01:01:07,000 --> 01:01:15,000
Then there was a man there from Mississippi who had already, he was older than we were.

341
01:01:15,000 --> 01:01:20,000
And he had been in the military, had been a second lieutenant.

342
01:01:20,000 --> 01:01:26,000
And he was at the SNCC meeting and heard about Julian Bond.

343
01:01:26,000 --> 01:01:28,000
So he came to work.

344
01:01:28,000 --> 01:01:39,000
So this became the nucleus for the Atlanta project of SNCC, which started out as Julian Bond re-election campaign.

345
01:01:39,000 --> 01:01:52,000
And we were to base ourselves in one of the poorest.

346
01:01:52,000 --> 01:01:54,000
Okay.

347
01:01:54,000 --> 01:01:55,000
Okay.

348
01:01:55,000 --> 01:01:57,000
So we're here to describe the Atlanta project again, please.

349
01:01:57,000 --> 01:01:58,000
Okay.

350
01:01:59,000 --> 01:02:01,000
Go back to the people.

351
01:02:01,000 --> 01:02:12,000
Okay. So this, what became the Atlanta project of SNCC started out as Julian Bond re-election campaign.

352
01:02:12,000 --> 01:02:24,000
And we were to set up our campaign headquarters in the poorest and most rundown area of Atlanta.

353
01:02:24,000 --> 01:02:27,000
And it was called Vine City (Atlanta) (Atlanta).

354
01:02:27,000 --> 01:02:30,000
It's now where the stadium is.

355
01:02:30,000 --> 01:02:43,000
And all, you know, it's, you just, when I go there now, I'm so disoriented because downtown Atlanta has eaten that whole area up of Shacks and, you know, just terrible, terrible.

356
01:02:44,000 --> 01:02:56,000
So we set up Julian Bond's re-election campaign at Vine City (Atlanta) (Atlanta) in Vine City (Atlanta) (Atlanta), the main street that ran through.

357
01:02:56,000 --> 01:03:02,000
And little shotgun house and all around us.

358
01:03:02,000 --> 01:03:13,000
The issues that have not been addressed to this day poor housing, huge unemployment.

359
01:03:13,000 --> 01:03:20,000
First time I'd ever seen a drug addict to know that somebody would tell me what was wrong with that person.

360
01:03:21,000 --> 01:03:26,000
I never knew anything about anyone having a drug problem.

361
01:03:26,000 --> 01:03:28,000
Alcoholism.

362
01:03:28,000 --> 01:03:30,000
Bad schools.

363
01:03:30,000 --> 01:03:33,000
This is what we confronted.

364
01:03:33,000 --> 01:03:40,000
And right around the corner was the Nation of Islam Mosque #15 (Atlanta) also.

365
01:03:41,000 --> 01:03:47,000
And so, you know, here we are trying to get Julian re-elected, which we did.

366
01:03:47,000 --> 01:03:49,000
We were very successful.

367
01:03:49,000 --> 01:03:51,000
People turned out to vote.

368
01:03:51,000 --> 01:03:53,000
He was re-elected.

369
01:03:53,000 --> 01:04:01,000
But he still had to get, you know, a congressional action to get his seat.

370
01:04:02,000 --> 01:04:08,000
So, you know, this was fodder for the people who say, you say, you're not an American.

371
01:04:08,000 --> 01:04:11,000
You're not really Americans.

372
01:04:11,000 --> 01:04:16,000
There's a problem way deeper than civil rights here, you know.

373
01:04:16,000 --> 01:04:24,000
So this was a thing that had my mind wondering, is the solution integration?

374
01:04:25,000 --> 01:04:28,000
Can we really integrate?

375
01:04:28,000 --> 01:04:30,000
Will they ever let us?

376
01:04:30,000 --> 01:04:35,000
Will we be accepted as full citizens ever?

377
01:04:35,000 --> 01:04:45,000
Or is race so deep that it will never ever be erased so that we will be seen as Americans?

378
01:04:45,000 --> 01:04:51,000
So these were the things, you know, we started talking about as a group.

379
01:04:52,000 --> 01:04:56,000
It's part of the measure of how you're thinking and evolving and you're working through these issues.

380
01:04:56,000 --> 01:04:58,000
It's part of the measure of that.

381
01:04:58,000 --> 01:05:04,000
I'm interested, what was your perspective on first the move to,

382
01:05:04,000 --> 01:05:15,000
move whites out of SNCC and then Stokely Carmichael's election kind of to upend John Lewis's run in 1966?

383
01:05:15,000 --> 01:05:22,000
We see this is all a part of that because what happens is that in the Atlanta project,

384
01:05:22,000 --> 01:05:29,000
we started to discuss them where do we go from here as a movement and as a people.

385
01:05:29,000 --> 01:05:34,000
And that nucleus that I've mentioned and others joined us,

386
01:05:34,000 --> 01:05:44,000
we literally started with a Wollensak tape recorder sitting around discussing these issues.

387
01:05:45,000 --> 01:05:54,000
And as often was the case myself and two other women would type up these discussions.

388
01:05:54,000 --> 01:06:03,000
And that became a document that was later credited to Stokely Carmichael as being the author,

389
01:06:03,000 --> 01:06:12,000
but it was a group project that had authored what became the position paper on Black Power.

390
01:06:13,000 --> 01:06:19,000
So what another important point is that after Mississippi Summer,

391
01:06:19,000 --> 01:06:31,000
the racial composition of SNCC changed because so many of the white volunteers wanted to commit their lives to full time.

392
01:06:31,000 --> 01:06:39,000
And so the organization expanded and the numbers changed in terms of the ratio.

393
01:06:39,000 --> 01:06:48,000
Now the Atlanta office, the National Headquarters, had a significant number of whites.

394
01:06:48,000 --> 01:07:01,000
And one of the problems that fed the feeling that whites needed to go and organize in the white community

395
01:07:01,000 --> 01:07:11,000
was that we would have to go there and often ask for resources and justify them to white members.

396
01:07:11,000 --> 01:07:16,000
And so we'd say, well wait a minute, is this a black organization?

397
01:07:16,000 --> 01:07:26,000
Or what? You know, and we had some difficulty after we got joined elected as we continued being a project wanting to

398
01:07:26,000 --> 01:07:31,000
and attacking these deep-seated issues that we still have not addressed,

399
01:07:31,000 --> 01:07:36,000
we had to justify ourselves often to predominantly white.

400
01:07:36,000 --> 01:07:42,000
So we would say, but wait a minute, you know, you guys need to go into the white community.

401
01:07:42,000 --> 01:07:47,000
So what happened was it got projected as an anti-white thing.

402
01:07:47,000 --> 01:07:55,000
Now there was some racial tension, but it was about we cannot change the white community.

403
01:07:55,000 --> 01:08:04,000
Possibly you can. Maybe you can't, but clearly we can't even go into the white community to try to even organize.

404
01:08:04,000 --> 01:08:07,000
So that's really what our position was.

405
01:08:07,000 --> 01:08:15,000
You go and work in your communities. We should run the black movement.

406
01:08:15,000 --> 01:08:19,000
And we need to see where we want to go.

407
01:08:19,000 --> 01:08:28,000
We noticed that, you know, if you played a Malcolm X tape, like we would do, not a tape, but a record,

408
01:08:28,000 --> 01:08:33,000
we sort of created some innovative ways of trying to organize.

409
01:08:33,000 --> 01:08:41,000
So we started having, we had a truck and we put a loudspeaker on it and we'd go to a vacant lot.

410
01:08:41,000 --> 01:08:48,000
And the way we could get people out, we'd have food, hot dogs, and then we'd get the people to come.

411
01:08:48,000 --> 01:08:51,000
So we could talk to them about registering the vote and stuff.

412
01:08:51,000 --> 01:08:59,000
But we noticed if you played, you know, somebody like Malcolm, the people would just come out and listen.

413
01:08:59,000 --> 01:09:04,000
And so it was like, do the people want integration?

414
01:09:04,000 --> 01:09:11,000
Or is this what the black leadership and under white direction have always said is the solution?

415
01:09:11,000 --> 01:09:17,000
So we began looking at some of these issues and this spreads through SNCC.

416
01:09:17,000 --> 01:09:23,000
So you have Bob Moses and his group who are now not in Mississippi anymore.

417
01:09:23,000 --> 01:09:29,000
They're working in Lowndes County, Alabama, along with Stokely.

418
01:09:29,000 --> 01:09:35,000
So a lot is going on as, and then people have gone to Africa.

419
01:09:35,000 --> 01:09:38,000
SNCC folk, a number of them went there.

420
01:09:38,000 --> 01:09:44,000
And so some people were saying, well, maybe really African Americans need to go back to Africa.

421
01:09:44,000 --> 01:09:48,000
So you know, all of this is swirling around.

422
01:09:48,000 --> 01:09:54,000
And when Stokely stands up in Mississippi and says, black power.

423
01:09:54,000 --> 01:09:58,000
And this catches fire with the people.

424
01:09:58,000 --> 01:10:05,000
So many factors start impinging on what was happening in the movement.

425
01:10:05,000 --> 01:10:10,000
Jim was losing control because he clearly did not approve of any of this.

426
01:10:10,000 --> 01:10:15,000
In spite of what he later went on to do, you know, but at that time.

427
01:10:15,000 --> 01:10:27,000
And of course, John Lewis, who was deeply religious and believed deeply in nonviolence, not as attacked, but as a way of life, being a minister.

428
01:10:27,000 --> 01:10:34,000
And all he opposed just talking about, you know, black power and all of this.

429
01:10:34,000 --> 01:10:42,000
So there was a real division that came to exist within SNCC around these issues.

430
01:10:42,000 --> 01:11:00,000
And, you know, in all fairness, people like Bob Zellner, whom I've had a face to face with after so many years of him having such pain over what me and my group were about.

431
01:11:00,000 --> 01:11:12,000
We gathered in Chicago at the invitation of a professor there to in front of his class and other people talk about this break.

432
01:11:12,000 --> 01:11:26,000
That often is not talked about amongst the SNCC people, the pain that's a white students volunteers felt particularly those who hadn't just gone down there during the summer.

433
01:11:26,000 --> 01:11:33,000
They'd been there from the beginning. And in the case of Bob Zellner, his folks were members of the clan. He couldn't go home.

434
01:11:33,000 --> 01:11:47,000
I mean, they threatened to kill him. So I didn't know that until we sat and talked about this two or three years ago to find out that by him SNCC was home.

435
01:11:47,000 --> 01:11:58,000
And so for me to say, you go back to the white community and they would kill me there. You know, I couldn't go back any more than you could go.

436
01:11:58,000 --> 01:12:08,000
So this was a very heavy time in SNCC. And I think, you know, led to the demise of the organization over time.

437
01:12:08,000 --> 01:12:15,000
Well, so other factors too are on this list. And let me ask you about the statement against the Vietnam War.

438
01:12:15,000 --> 01:12:17,000
Oh, yeah. That's certainly.

439
01:12:17,000 --> 01:12:25,000
Yeah. The statement, short while further down the road about Israel.

440
01:12:25,000 --> 01:12:26,000
Oh, yeah.

441
01:12:26,000 --> 01:12:27,000
Oh, right.

442
01:12:27,000 --> 01:12:33,000
You guys have in front of you some questions that are still on resolve.

443
01:12:33,000 --> 01:12:35,000
Yeah. That's internationally.

444
01:12:35,000 --> 01:12:37,000
It's so funnily. Yeah.

445
01:12:37,000 --> 01:12:39,000
You weren't fairly pointing.

446
01:12:39,000 --> 01:12:40,000
Yeah.

447
01:12:40,000 --> 01:12:42,000
Very complicated. Exactly. Exactly.

448
01:12:42,000 --> 01:12:45,000
Yeah. You know, okay.

449
01:12:45,000 --> 01:12:46,000
Okay.

450
01:12:46,000 --> 01:12:47,000
We're back on it.

451
01:12:47,000 --> 01:12:48,000
Yeah. Yeah.

452
01:12:48,000 --> 01:12:52,000
Yeah. That's where I've, you know, it's so interesting.

453
01:12:52,000 --> 01:13:00,000
I, and I'm not thinking of her name right now. I hope I'll be seeing her in Chicago.

454
01:13:00,000 --> 01:13:09,000
The woman that drafted SNCC Palestinian/Israel statement, I'd forgotten who had done that, but she was after reunion.

455
01:13:09,000 --> 01:13:18,000
And she, and I started talking and she mentioned that she was the person who wrote the initial draft of that.

456
01:13:18,000 --> 01:13:27,000
And I just had forgotten all about how that created a firestorm against SNCC, you know.

457
01:13:28,000 --> 01:13:39,000
As, and I was very involved with the Vietnam, anti-Vietnam war statement, the drafting and the working on that, but I had not been at all on the Palestinian issue.

458
01:13:39,000 --> 01:13:48,000
So this woman, I'm hoping to interview her when I'm out in Chicago in October for a Chicago the SNCC reunion.

459
01:13:48,000 --> 01:13:49,000
Yeah.

460
01:13:49,000 --> 01:13:55,000
What was the vision? Tell me if you would.

461
01:13:55,000 --> 01:14:11,000
When you gathered, when the, when the SNCC folks, this new SNCC emphasis gathered up its best thinking and its best effort to envision a better strategy for the future.

462
01:14:11,000 --> 01:14:15,000
What, how would you describe that?

463
01:14:15,000 --> 01:14:24,000
Do you mean at that time where, where, where we, I'm not sure that we had a,

464
01:14:24,000 --> 01:14:30,000
a vision that had coalesced at all?

465
01:14:30,000 --> 01:14:43,000
Interestingly, the Atlanta Project staff got together. We sort of had a mini reunion and we're hoping to put together a book, which would be wonderful.

466
01:14:43,000 --> 01:14:52,000
I'm supposed to help edit it and to try to see as best we can where we're out thoughts.

467
01:14:52,000 --> 01:15:16,000
Because as I look back on it, I don't think I knew. I think it was very much questioning what I had believed in, wondering if some of these other ideas that had been a part of Black thought from slavery forward, you know, and I didn't even realize that,

468
01:15:16,000 --> 01:15:34,000
that there's always sort of been this two pronged thing one that fought to integrate into the country, others that wanted to leave or certainly to create a space within this country for African Americans.

469
01:15:34,000 --> 01:15:52,000
So I think that we didn't know that we were questioning, wondering what our relationship was to Africa, wondering what, if it not integration, then what?

470
01:15:52,000 --> 01:15:59,000
Can you describe your transition away from SNCC?

471
01:15:59,000 --> 01:16:13,000
Well, first of all, pretty much being thrown out of SNCC, you know, in the sense that SNCC was ending the Atlanta Project as a project was expelled from SNCC.

472
01:16:13,000 --> 01:16:26,000
So I went to work for the National Council of Negro Women and they caught me, you know, with not having any idea of what I was going to do.

473
01:16:26,000 --> 01:16:33,000
It really came as a shock when the project was basically told we were no longer a part of the organization.

474
01:16:33,000 --> 01:16:35,000
Can you flush that out a little bit, though?

475
01:16:35,000 --> 01:16:39,000
Well, you know, it's so interesting.

476
01:16:39,000 --> 01:16:47,000
On overtly, what happened is different from all that was going on underneath.

477
01:16:47,000 --> 01:16:57,000
What had happened was someone sent a check for, I believe it was $3,000 to the Atlanta Project.

478
01:16:57,000 --> 01:17:05,000
And we were told by James Forman that under no circumstances was that our money.

479
01:17:05,000 --> 01:17:13,000
I think it was sent to SNCC, but sent to our address, and we put it in the Atlanta Project account.

480
01:17:13,000 --> 01:17:18,000
Well, when that came out, that became the hot button issue.

481
01:17:18,000 --> 01:17:22,000
That, you know, we were supposed to turn the money over.

482
01:17:22,000 --> 01:17:26,000
We said, we're not, you know, we're going to use it in our work.

483
01:17:26,000 --> 01:17:31,000
And then they said, you have to.

484
01:17:31,000 --> 01:17:35,000
And so then there was a lawyer was brought in.

485
01:17:35,000 --> 01:17:47,000
And we literally fought over, I don't mean physically, but that was the basis for which we were actually put out of the organization.

486
01:17:47,000 --> 01:17:51,000
So, but that was on the top.

487
01:17:51,000 --> 01:18:03,000
But underneath, as Jim saw, I said, is a totally disruptive element pulling the organization away from the direction in which it had been going and was going.

488
01:18:03,000 --> 01:18:09,000
And that we needed to be put out. So we were.

489
01:18:09,000 --> 01:18:12,000
Yeah.

490
01:18:12,000 --> 01:18:22,000
Maybe since we just got right in that moment about Jim Forman perspective on kind of the arc of his future thereafter.

491
01:18:22,000 --> 01:18:28,000
Well, I, you know, and I really regret I never had a real conversation with him.

492
01:18:28,000 --> 01:18:32,000
You know, I was angry. And here was someone whom I loved.

493
01:18:32,000 --> 01:18:36,000
So, you know, he'd been my mentor. I looked up to him.

494
01:18:36,000 --> 01:18:43,000
And to end our relationship on that note, you know, was terrible.

495
01:18:43,000 --> 01:18:55,000
And I really regret it. And then to see him become in the forefront of an aspect of Black Power, you know, over the years.

496
01:18:55,000 --> 01:19:00,000
And I really regret we never talked, you know, about that.

497
01:19:00,000 --> 01:19:13,000
But I felt that the issues that he worked on, you know, becoming so visible in the effort to, for reparations from the churches.

498
01:19:13,000 --> 01:19:20,000
And, you know, that was an amazing thing to me. And I wondered what happened in his mind.

499
01:19:20,000 --> 01:19:25,000
And I don't know if anyone has, you know, interviewed him before he passed away.

500
01:19:25,000 --> 01:19:35,000
If we'll get any of that, an understanding of what happened that changed him from the integrationist path, you know.

501
01:19:35,000 --> 01:19:36,000
Yeah.

502
01:19:36,000 --> 01:19:41,000
I mean, I was a couple of things.

503
01:19:41,000 --> 01:19:46,000
Did you have to, for how much did you think about in these years?

504
01:19:46,000 --> 01:19:50,000
And we can pick this question up, reaching back, say, to Mississippi.

505
01:19:50,000 --> 01:20:15,000
How much did you think from 64 to 68? How often did you think in how much thought did you give to the question of, I'm thinking of the many ways that the White apparatus of law enforcement authority moved to undermine domestic organizations that they did not come in.

506
01:20:15,000 --> 01:20:26,000
Go and tell pro and all the other many ways that that kind of work was done. Was that something that you confronted? How much did you think about it? You see it in your own?

507
01:20:26,000 --> 01:20:28,000
Did you encounter that directly?

508
01:20:28,000 --> 01:20:40,000
Well, it's so interesting because, you know, having lived about seven different lives, I went to work for the American Friends Service Committee on that very issue.

509
01:20:40,000 --> 01:20:58,000
It was called the, what was it? The project on government surveillance and civil liberties or something like that. I can't quite remember the, the title had a long title, but that was exactly the work of that project.

510
01:20:58,000 --> 01:21:13,000
And I was recruited and became the assistant director and my role was to travel across the country and interview, never heard the term or history, but now I know that's what I was doing.

511
01:21:13,000 --> 01:21:28,000
A lot of it on tape, people in not only the African American movement, but in the American Indian Movement in the the Brown Berets, the black Panther Party,

512
01:21:28,000 --> 01:21:43,000
and the Rodolfo "Corky" Gonzales and his group, I literally interviewed people from those organizations about the role of Coentel Pro in destroying their movements.

513
01:21:43,000 --> 01:22:00,000
And that project was funded by the Ford Foundation and others. We had staff in Mississippi. Ken Lawrence was our staff who did so much work on the Mississippi State Sovereignty Commission.

514
01:22:00,000 --> 01:22:12,000
Ken is still in Mississippi. We had a person on staff in Chicago, person out on the West Coast, getting one of the main things we did.

515
01:22:12,000 --> 01:22:26,000
And the main thing we did was to get these individuals and their organizations to get their files under the Freedom of Information Act and to share those files with us.

516
01:22:26,000 --> 01:22:37,000
So all that material is there at the American Friends Service Committee's office in 1501 Cherry Street in Philadelphia.

517
01:22:37,000 --> 01:22:52,000
So not all, I mean, did I ever get to think about this and interview people about this and learn how these agencies, first of all, were spying on us.

518
01:22:52,000 --> 01:23:12,000
And the reason American Friends Service Committee got involved was because they found out not only would they, as an organization, being spied upon, but all of these Quaker meetings had infiltrators in the Quaker meetings reporting back to the FBI on the Quakers.

519
01:23:12,000 --> 01:23:29,000
And when they found that out, they were furious. That's why they launched this project. And of course, we partnered with the American Civil Liberties Union, the National Lawyers Guild, and some of the other civil liberties organizations to mount this project.

520
01:23:29,000 --> 01:23:44,000
But that's when I really learned that right there in Mississippi, a number of the FBI agents were feeding information to the Sorcery Commission and possibly to the plan.

521
01:23:44,000 --> 01:23:59,000
And I mean, this was a shock. The people that we thought were there to protect us, and I knew they would come around and talk to us. And we talked freely to them, not knowing.

522
01:23:59,000 --> 01:24:28,000
You know, this stuff was being fed right back to the people who were trying to stop what we were doing. I think one of the really shocking things was when I interviewed people who had been in the apartment when Fred Hampton had been shot, because I did a lot of work with Black Panther Party people actually was taken to the apartment there in Chicago to see it.

523
01:24:29,000 --> 01:24:45,000
And found out that his bodyguard had drugged them so that there hadn't been any shots fired from inside. It was an assassination, you know, by the Chicago police and the FBI.

524
01:24:45,000 --> 01:24:57,000
And in California, you know, I interviewed Panther members, members of us, how they were pitted against one another by agents provocateurs.

525
01:24:57,000 --> 01:25:12,000
I mean, this was shocking stuff to learn that our own government, people we thought were there to protect us, or in many cases were there to disrupt these organizations.

526
01:25:12,000 --> 01:25:16,000
But it had not been, it sounded like not been much on your mind.

527
01:25:16,000 --> 01:25:17,000
No.

528
01:25:17,000 --> 01:25:32,000
Not, I mean, you know, we didn't, if I know once there was a guy that joined our project, and we were all a little worried about him because he was a white Mississippi and that was unusual.

529
01:25:32,000 --> 01:25:52,000
And, you know, we didn't know if it was rumor, if he was a spy, you know, but it was sort of like I said, well, we want somebody like him to become a part, but a number of the members of our project there in Laurel said this guy is a spy, you know, watch it, be careful.

530
01:25:52,000 --> 01:26:02,000
But really, we were so open, you know, and just didn't know about this apparatus at all.

531
01:26:02,000 --> 01:26:03,000
Yeah.

532
01:26:03,000 --> 01:26:06,000
Let me reach back to the question we touched on.

533
01:26:06,000 --> 01:26:17,000
Good while I was on the interview, and that was dealing with both the near term and the much longer term effects of having really been through traumatic circumstances.

534
01:26:17,000 --> 01:26:29,000
You mentioned so interesting that you mentioned that, you know, on emerging from the 15 days of horrible incarceration and all that terror and trauma that you experienced in the context like that, you come out and you're in two car accidents just like that.

535
01:26:29,000 --> 01:26:32,000
I mean, don't even really know how it happened.

536
01:26:32,000 --> 01:26:33,000
Yeah.

537
01:26:33,000 --> 01:26:42,000
So that's a very, actually, suggested manifestation of just being so overcome in other ways by what you've just experienced.

538
01:26:42,000 --> 01:26:52,000
How about, have you thought about, have there been ways you've seen echoes of that kind of experience emerged later in your life?

539
01:26:52,000 --> 01:27:02,000
I don't mean car accidents, I mean, you know, they could become, they could, they could become things that have echoes of all different sorts.

540
01:27:02,000 --> 01:27:14,000
I mean, perhaps positive in ways, but others very difficult, and I just wonder, so many people, I'm asking this because so many people who came through the movement and encountered all of this violence and all this.

541
01:27:14,000 --> 01:27:19,000
It would manifest in different ways, sometimes years later.

542
01:27:19,000 --> 01:27:21,000
Like flashbacks or something?

543
01:27:21,000 --> 01:27:26,000
It could be, it could be bad, it could be a decision, I need to go move and live somewhere else for a couple of years.

544
01:27:26,000 --> 01:27:28,000
I mean, to have an Africa for a year and a decade.

545
01:27:28,000 --> 01:27:29,000
Right.

546
01:27:29,000 --> 01:27:50,000
I guess in my case, you know, up until I came into academia, I guess I've just been so busy, you know, because from one, you know, movement to another, I really didn't take a break.

547
01:27:50,000 --> 01:28:03,000
And I don't know, I don't recall being what I considered a damaged long term, you know.

548
01:28:03,000 --> 01:28:04,000
I didn't mean to.

549
01:28:04,000 --> 01:28:08,000
Yeah, no, no, it would be fine if you did mean it.

550
01:28:08,000 --> 01:28:13,000
People have to struggle with these, but I mean, these things have, they're not trivial things.

551
01:28:13,000 --> 01:28:14,000
No.

552
01:28:14,000 --> 01:28:15,000
No.

553
01:28:15,000 --> 01:28:17,000
The matter is a very serious consequence.

554
01:28:17,000 --> 01:28:22,000
Well, I don't think I've ever left them behind, you know.

555
01:28:22,000 --> 01:28:35,000
I think that, and I think working with students has helped me to see because as I try to communicate to them those times,

556
01:28:35,000 --> 01:28:41,000
and I realize they just look at me like, what is, you know, what is she talking about?

557
01:28:41,000 --> 01:28:54,000
And I rely a lot on the films of the movement because nobody who's, you know, 19, 20 years old growing up in this country can believe that this kind of stuff was happening.

558
01:28:54,000 --> 01:29:02,000
And so in one way to have a person who's still able to talk and walk and see, tell them, it happened to me.

559
01:29:02,000 --> 01:29:17,000
I'm telling you, and then I bring in some of the civil rights vets from the Atlanta, from here in Gainesville to tell their stories, and we have some films of them, and all trying to communicate that.

560
01:29:18,000 --> 01:29:33,000
But I think that it just, what it has done for me is, makes me know that human beings can do very, very bad things to one another.

561
01:29:34,000 --> 01:29:46,000
And I guess the years of working with American Friends Service Committee and being a part of the first Americans to go into Cambodia after the fall of Pol Pot,

562
01:29:46,000 --> 01:30:02,000
and to see the mountain of skulls and bones there, as a part of a small group that was flown in by the Vietnamese military to see it.

563
01:30:02,000 --> 01:30:12,000
And to talk to the few people who were still left in Phnom Penh who told us their stories, oral histories again, right?

564
01:30:12,000 --> 01:30:14,000
Of what they had lived through.

565
01:30:14,000 --> 01:30:24,000
I think, you know, that helped me to understand that this is a human problem.

566
01:30:24,000 --> 01:30:29,000
You know, what we can do to one another, you know.

567
01:30:29,000 --> 01:30:56,000
So it definitely, along with my movement into Sufism, the mystical stream in Islam, I think that probably has had such an impact on me understanding this is a human condition, that it needs not only do we have to change things legally, politically structurally.

568
01:30:56,000 --> 01:31:02,000
We also have to change things in people's hearts and their spirits.

569
01:31:02,000 --> 01:31:17,000
And I think that's what helped me to come around to understanding Dr. King's message in a way that I had not, and I had rejected, you know, and it brought me sort of full circle.

570
01:31:17,000 --> 01:31:36,000
Back to nonviolence is the only real way to bring about a change that doesn't leave corpses, piled mountains high or even just wounded spirits and souls and bodies.

571
01:31:36,000 --> 01:31:49,000
So that has a lot to do with my coming back around to seeing how right he was and how it's the only way.

572
01:31:49,000 --> 01:31:54,000
No matter how difficult it might be to do it.

573
01:31:54,000 --> 01:32:15,000
And it isn't easy, you know, it's not the easy way, but it's the only way that you might be left with people who can work together and move forward without the pain and all you have when it's been warfare or massacres and the light, you know.

574
01:32:15,000 --> 01:32:22,000
Oh, it's just one sec. We're back on.

575
01:32:22,000 --> 01:32:35,000
Let me ask to kind of bring us to a conclusion here, and I, of course, acknowledge that any conversation like this is such a tiny way to engage the story in your life and all the work that you've done.

576
01:32:35,000 --> 01:32:51,000
But it isn't a story that ends in the late 60s. It's that you carry all of this forward with you into very passionate engagement with a range of progressive causes and activist causes.

577
01:32:51,000 --> 01:33:03,000
And you also engage in a very lovely and involved personal spiritual evolution.

578
01:33:03,000 --> 01:33:14,000
And my sense is that some of that long path has brought you, and I've seen in your writings, to a point of new perspective, retrospective.

579
01:33:14,000 --> 01:33:30,000
Yes. Yes. I definitely made a few loops and sort of come back around to some earlier beliefs.

580
01:33:30,000 --> 01:33:50,000
The one certainly very dire moment in terms of my feeling, tremendous feeling of despair for this country, for black people in this country, was when Dr. King was assassinated.

581
01:33:50,000 --> 01:34:13,000
That was a very low point for so many of us. But in my case, I experienced it feeling I was in a totally alien situation at a hotel in Manhattan where I had gone to attend a meeting for the National Council of Negro Women.

582
01:34:13,000 --> 01:34:23,000
And I learned he had been killed. And so I dropped my bags and hopped on a subway and went back up to Harlem and just hung out.

583
01:34:23,000 --> 01:34:34,000
And rioting going on. And I didn't know anybody. But when people ran, I ran. Fires were started.

584
01:34:34,000 --> 01:34:57,000
I was in a riot. But I just felt that I had to vent in some way. But a few years after that, I had for a long time carried after 68, a lot of anger toward the country.

585
01:34:57,000 --> 01:35:09,000
And I believe that it was quite probable that our government had had had him assassinated. I didn't buy the one man story.

586
01:35:09,000 --> 01:35:32,000
So I was pretty, pretty messed up in terms of how I felt about the country and why America and all. And then I meet a Sufi mystic from Sri Lanka in 1971 and began studying Sufism, the mystical stream.

587
01:35:32,000 --> 01:35:52,000
And in Islam and really that those teachings about the human condition and that our life really is a school where we learn things.

588
01:35:52,000 --> 01:36:07,000
And that the design from a Sufi perspective is that you learn to embrace the good and to reject the bad in all aspects of your life, no matter what.

589
01:36:07,000 --> 01:36:19,000
And you know, that was hard for me to take. And even with studying with this teacher, M.R. M.R. M.R. Bawa Muhaiyaddeen Muhaiyaddeen Muhaiyaddeen, I spent 17 years with him.

590
01:36:19,000 --> 01:36:37,000
Gradually, you know, I began to see the wisdom in that. And it also caused me to reflect back upon Dr. King and his teachings and my own upbringing in the Christian church.

591
01:36:37,000 --> 01:37:04,000
And to re-embrace nonviolence as the only way to bring about deep social change that will last. So this is a sort of came back to my Christian teachings of Jesus as well as Dr. King through Sufism, the mystical stream in Islam.

592
01:37:04,000 --> 01:37:11,000
Thank you very sincerely and it's been a real privilege and an honor to spend this time with you. Thank you so much.

593
01:37:11,000 --> 01:37:23,000
Oh, it's been great to be able to share my story and just to think this will be somewhere long after I'm gone. I'm happy to share for whatever good it might do.

594
01:37:23,000 --> 01:37:29,000
Thank you so much. Thank you. Thank you. Wow.

595
01:37:29,000 --> 01:37:39,000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

